nodes.label: Alex reports that their shoulders are up by their ears.

data.text: Alex reports that their shoulders are up by their ears.
data.supporting_evidence: Alex’s direct somatic observation during the session.

nodes.label: Alex feels a pulsing heat running from the shoulders to the upper back.

data.text: Alex feels a pulsing heat running from the shoulders to the upper back.
data.supporting_evidence: Alex’s embodied description while focusing on the sensation.

nodes.label: Emails from Alex’s boss trigger a bracing-for-impact response.

data.text: Emails from Alex’s boss trigger a bracing-for-impact response.
data.supporting_evidence: Alex’s associative link between external stimuli and bodily reaction.

nodes.label: The tension in Alex’s body seems to express 'I can't do enough. It's never going to be enough.'

data.text: The tension in Alex’s body seems to express 'I can't do enough. It's never going to be enough.'
data.supporting_evidence: Alex’s emotional attribution of a verbal message to the somatic tension.

nodes.label: Alex associates the current tension with memories of their father’s high expectations.

data.text: Alex associates the current tension with memories of their father’s high expectations.
data.supporting_evidence: Alex’s spontaneous recollection prompted by bodily awareness.

nodes.label: Placing one hand on the heart and one on the stomach feels supportive for Alex.

data.text: Placing one hand on the heart and one on the stomach feels supportive for Alex.
data.supporting_evidence: Alex’s immediate subjective report after following Dr. Wilson’s suggestion.

nodes.label: Alex’s shoulders dropped slightly after the supportive hand placement.

data.text: Alex’s shoulders dropped slightly after the supportive hand placement.
data.supporting_evidence: Alex’s real-time observation of a physical shift.

nodes.label: Alex perceives more spaciousness and room to breathe.

data.text: Alex perceives more spaciousness and room to breathe.
data.supporting_evidence: Alex’s experiential report during the exercise.

nodes.label: The tension remains but no longer feels overwhelming to Alex.

data.text: The tension remains but no longer feels overwhelming to Alex.
data.supporting_evidence: Alex’s concluding summary of the exercise’s effect.

nodes.label: The body reliably stores and communicates unresolved emotional memories.

data.text: The body reliably stores and communicates unresolved emotional memories.
data.inference_rationale: Dr. Wilson’s invitation to let the bodily tension “speak” and Alex’s immediate connection between shoulder tightness and childhood memories with Dad assume that physical sensations are meaningful carriers of past emotional experiences rather than random discomfort.

nodes.label: Verbal insight alone is insufficient for healing; bodily intervention is necessary.

data.text: Verbal insight alone is insufficient for healing; bodily intervention is necessary.
data.inference_rationale: After Alex has already articulated the link between workplace stress and paternal expectations, Dr. Wilson still proposes a somatic experiment (hands on heart and stomach), implying that cognitive understanding is not enough—direct bodily engagement is required to shift the emotional state.

nodes.label: Self-touch in a therapeutic context is safe and effective for emotional regulation.

data.text: Self-touch in a therapeutic context is safe and effective for emotional regulation.
data.inference_rationale: Dr. Wilson confidently instructs Alex to place hands on vulnerable body areas without first asking whether Alex feels safe doing so, suggesting an assumption that this intervention is inherently safe and will yield regulatory benefits.

nodes.label: Workplace authority figures re-trigger early attachment wounds.

data.text: Workplace authority figures re-trigger early attachment wounds.
data.inference_rationale: Alex seamlessly equates “an email from my boss” with “bracing for impact” and then links it to dad’s high expectations, implying that the nervous system treats the boss as a symbolic father whose approval is still urgently sought.

nodes.label: Small, moment-to-moment somatic shifts can rapidly reduce emotional overwhelm.

data.text: Small, moment-to-moment somatic shifts can rapidly reduce emotional overwhelm.
data.inference_rationale: Alex reports that after only a few seconds of hand placement and breathing, the tension becomes “not overwhelming,” suggesting the therapy frame believes brief, targeted somatic actions can produce immediate, meaningful relief.

nodes.label: Tense. I can feel tightness in my shoulders.

data.text: Tense. I can feel tightness in my shoulders.
data.context: Immediate bodily awareness signaling stress in the present moment

nodes.label: My shoulders are up by my ears... pulsing heat running down to my upper back.

data.text: My shoulders are up by my ears... pulsing heat running down to my upper back.
data.context: Heightened sympathetic arousal triggered by workplace reminders

nodes.label: Every time I get an email from my boss, I feel like I'm bracing for impact.

data.text: Every time I get an email from my boss, I feel like I'm bracing for impact.
data.context: Chronic hyper-vigilance linked to authority figures and performance pressure

nodes.label: "I can't do enough. It's never going to be enough."

data.text: "I can't do enough. It's never going to be enough."
data.context: Core belief of inadequacy rooted in historical paternal criticism

nodes.label: It feels supportive. My shoulders just dropped a little.

data.text: It feels supportive. My shoulders just dropped a little.
data.context: Initial co-regulation from therapeutic presence and self-touch

nodes.label: More spaciousness... tension is still there, but doesn't feel overwhelming.

data.text: More spaciousness... tension is still there, but doesn't feel overwhelming.
data.context: Shift from sympathetic to parasympathetic dominance; reduced threat perception

claims.text: Alex reports that their shoulders are up by their ears.
claims.supporting_evidence: Alex’s direct somatic observation during the session.

claims.text: Alex feels a pulsing heat running from the shoulders to the upper back.
claims.supporting_evidence: Alex’s embodied description while focusing on the sensation.

claims.text: Emails from Alex’s boss trigger a bracing-for-impact response.
claims.supporting_evidence: Alex’s associative link between external stimuli and bodily reaction.

claims.text: The tension in Alex’s body seems to express 'I can't do enough. It's never going to be enough.'
claims.supporting_evidence: Alex’s emotional attribution of a verbal message to the somatic tension.

claims.text: Alex associates the current tension with memories of their father’s high expectations.
claims.supporting_evidence: Alex’s spontaneous recollection prompted by bodily awareness.

claims.text: Placing one hand on the heart and one on the stomach feels supportive for Alex.
claims.supporting_evidence: Alex’s immediate subjective report after following Dr. Wilson’s suggestion.

claims.text: Alex’s shoulders dropped slightly after the supportive hand placement.
claims.supporting_evidence: Alex’s real-time observation of a physical shift.

claims.text: Alex perceives more spaciousness and room to breathe.
claims.supporting_evidence: Alex’s experiential report during the exercise.

claims.text: The tension remains but no longer feels overwhelming to Alex.
claims.supporting_evidence: Alex’s concluding summary of the exercise’s effect.

claims.text: The body reliably stores and communicates unresolved emotional memories.
claims.inference_rationale: Dr. Wilson’s invitation to let the bodily tension “speak” and Alex’s immediate connection between shoulder tightness and childhood memories with Dad assume that physical sensations are meaningful carriers of past emotional experiences rather than random discomfort.

claims.text: Verbal insight alone is insufficient for healing; bodily intervention is necessary.
claims.inference_rationale: After Alex has already articulated the link between workplace stress and paternal expectations, Dr. Wilson still proposes a somatic experiment (hands on heart and stomach), implying that cognitive understanding is not enough—direct bodily engagement is required to shift the emotional state.

claims.text: Self-touch in a therapeutic context is safe and effective for emotional regulation.
claims.inference_rationale: Dr. Wilson confidently instructs Alex to place hands on vulnerable body areas without first asking whether Alex feels safe doing so, suggesting an assumption that this intervention is inherently safe and will yield regulatory benefits.

claims.text: Workplace authority figures re-trigger early attachment wounds.
claims.inference_rationale: Alex seamlessly equates “an email from my boss” with “bracing for impact” and then links it to dad’s high expectations, implying that the nervous system treats the boss as a symbolic father whose approval is still urgently sought.

claims.text: Small, moment-to-moment somatic shifts can rapidly reduce emotional overwhelm.
claims.inference_rationale: Alex reports that after only a few seconds of hand placement and breathing, the tension becomes “not overwhelming,” suggesting the therapy frame believes brief, targeted somatic actions can produce immediate, meaningful relief.

claims.text: Tense. I can feel tightness in my shoulders.
claims.context: Immediate bodily awareness signaling stress in the present moment

claims.text: My shoulders are up by my ears... pulsing heat running down to my upper back.
claims.context: Heightened sympathetic arousal triggered by workplace reminders

claims.text: Every time I get an email from my boss, I feel like I'm bracing for impact.
claims.context: Chronic hyper-vigilance linked to authority figures and performance pressure

claims.text: "I can't do enough. It's never going to be enough."
claims.context: Core belief of inadequacy rooted in historical paternal criticism

claims.text: It feels supportive. My shoulders just dropped a little.
claims.context: Initial co-regulation from therapeutic presence and self-touch

claims.text: More spaciousness... tension is still there, but doesn't feel overwhelming.
claims.context: Shift from sympathetic to parasympathetic dominance; reduced threat perception
